    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.04 doesn't necessarily mean the drug \"definitely works.\" It just means that the observed effect is unlikely to occur by chance, assuming the null hypothesis is true (i.e., the drug has no effect on blood pressure). However, it's also possible that the p-value is due to random chance, and the true effect of the drug is actually smaller than what was observed.\n\nThink of it like a coin toss: just because you get 10 heads in a row, it doesn't mean the coin is biased towards heads. The p-value of 0.04 is like the probability of getting 10 heads in a row by chance, assuming the coin is fair. But it doesn't tell you anything about the true probability of getting heads on a single toss. The drug's actual effect on blood pressure might be smaller than the observed effect, but the p-value just tells you that the observed effect is unlikely to occur by chance, not that it's definitely real.",
      "source": "target",
